n\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t<td><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gluttony\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Gluttony\">Gluttony</a></td>\n\t\t\t<td><i>Gula</i></td>\n\t\t\t<td>&quot;Gola&quot;</td>\n\t\t\t<td><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Temperance_(virtue)\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Temperance (virtue)\">Temperance</a></td>\n\t\t\t<td><i>Moderatio</i></td>\n\t\t\t<td>&quot;Temperanza&quot;</td>\n\t\t</tr>\n\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t<td><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Greed\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Greed\">Greed</a></td>\n\t\t\t<td><i>Avaritia</i></td>\n\t\t\t<td>&quot;Avarizia&quot;</td>\n\t\t\t<td><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charity_(virtue)\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Charity (virtue)\">Charity</a> (or, sometimes, <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Generosity\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Generosity\">Generosity</a>)</td>\n\t\t\t<td><i>Caritas</i> (<i>Liberalitas</i>)</td>\n\t\t\t<td>&quot;Generosit&agrave;&quot;</td>\n\t\t</tr>\n\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t<td><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sloth_(deadly_sin)\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Sloth (deadly sin)\">Sloth</a></td>\n\t\t\t<td><i>Acedia</i></td>\n\t\t\t<td>&quot;Accidia&quot;</td>\n\t\t\t<td><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diligence\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Diligence\">Diligence</a></td>\n\t\t\t<td><i>Industria</i></td>\n\t\t\t<td>&quot;Diligenza&quot;</td>\n\t\t</tr>\n\t</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;<b>Arishadvarga</b> or <b>Shadripu </b>in Hinduism:</p>\n\n<ol>\n\t<li>Lust or desire <b>(<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sanskrit\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Sanskrit\">Sanskrit</a>: <a class=\"new\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=%E0%A4%95%E0%A4%BE%E0%A4%AE&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"काम (page does not exist)\">काम</a>)</b> &ndash; <i><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kama\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Kama\">Kama</a></i></li>\n\t<li>Anger <b>(<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sanskrit\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Sanskrit\">Sanskrit</a>: <a class=\"new\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=%E0%A4%95%E0%A5%8D%E0%A4%B0%E0%A5%8B%E0%A4%A7&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"क्रोध (page does not exist)\">क्रोध</a>)</b> &ndash; <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Krodha_(Mental_factor)\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Krodha (Mental factor)\"><i>Krodha</i></a></li>\n\t<li>Greed <b>(<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sanskrit\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Sanskrit\">Sanskrit</a>: <a class=\"new\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=%E0%A4%B2%E0%A5%8B%E0%A4%AD&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"लोभ (page does not exist)\">लोभ</a>)</b> &ndash; <i>Lobha</i></li>\n\t<li>Pride <b>(<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sanskrit\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Sanskrit\">Sanskrit</a>: <a class=\"new\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=%E0%A4%AE%E0%A4%A6&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"मद (page does not exist)\">मद</a>)</b> &ndash; <i><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mada\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Mada\">Mada</a></i> &ndash; pride, hubris, (being possessed by)</li>\n\t<li>Fascination or attachment <b>(<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sanskrit\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Sanskrit\">Sanskrit</a>: <a class=\"new\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=%E0%A4%AE%E0%A5%8B%E0%A4%B9&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"मोह (page does not exist)\">मोह</a>)</b> &ndash; <i>Moha</i> &ndash; delusory emotional attachment or temptation</li>\n\t<li>Jealousy <b>(<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sanskrit\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Sanskrit\">Sanskrit</a>: <a class=\"new\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=%E0%A4%AE%E0%A4%BE%E0%A4%A4%E0%A5%8D%E0%A4%B8%E0%A4%B0%E0%A5%8D%E0%A4%AF&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"मात्सर्य (page does not exist)\">मात्सर्य</a>)</b> &ndash; <i>Matsarya</i> &ndash; envy, jealousy</li>\n</ol>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p><strong>Poisons/Kleshas in Buddhism</strong></p>\n\n<p>In the Mahayana tradition, the five main kleshas are referred to as the <i><b>five poisons</b></i> (Sanskrit: <i>pa&ntilde;ca kleśaviṣa</i>; Tibetan-Wylie: <i>dug lnga</i>).</p>\n\n<table class=\"wikitable\" height=\"266\" width=\"871\">\n\t<tbody>\n\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t<th>Poison&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</th>\n\t\t\t<th>Sanskrit&nbsp;</th>\n\t\t\t<th>&nbsp;Pali</th>\n\t\t\t<th>&nbsp;Tibetan<sup>&nbsp;&nbsp; </sup></th>\n\t\t\t<th>Description</th>\n\t\t\t<th>Alternate translations</th>\n\t\t</tr>\n\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t<td>Ignorance</td>\n\t\t\t<td><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Moha_(Buddhism)\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Moha (Buddhism)\">moha</a><br />\n\t\t\t<a class=\"mw-redirect\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Avidya_(Buddhism)\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Avidya (Buddhism)\">avidya</a></td>\n\t\t\t<td>moha<br />\n\t\t\tavijja</td>\n\t\t\t<td>gti mug<br />\n\t\t\tma rig pa</td>\n\t\t\t<td>Lack of discernment; not understanding the way of things</td>\n\t\t\t<td>Confusion, bewilderment, delusion</td>\n\t\t</tr>\n\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t<td>Attachment</td>\n\t\t\t<td><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Raga_(Buddhism)\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Raga (Buddhism)\">rāga</a></td>\n\t\t\t<td>lobha</td>\n\t\t\t<td>&#39;dod chags</td>\n\t\t\t<td>Attachment or desire for what we like</td>\n\t\t\t<td>Desire, passion</td>\n\t\t</tr>\n\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t<td>Aversion</td>\n\t\t\t<td><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dvesha_(Buddhism)\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Dvesha (Buddhism)\">dvesha</a></td>\n\t\t\t<td>dosa</td>\n\t\t\t<td>zhe sdang</td>\n\t\t\t<td>Aversion for what we don&#39;t like, or for what prevents us from getting what we like</td>\n\t\t\t<td>Anger, hatred</td>\n\t\t</tr>\n\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t<td>Pride</td>\n\t\t\t<td><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/M%C4%81na\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Māna\">māna</a></td>\n\t\t\t<td>māna</td>\n\t\t\t<td>nga rgyal</td>\n\t\t\t<td>Having an inflated opinion of oneself and a disrespectful attitude toward others</td>\n\t\t\t<td>Arrogance, Conceit</td>\n\t\t</tr>\n\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t<td>Envy</td>\n\t\t\t<td><a class=\"mw-redirect\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Irshya\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Irshya\">irshya</a></td>\n\t\t\t<td>issā</td>\n\t\t\t<td>phrag dog</td>\n\t\t\t<td>Being unable to bear the accomplishments or good fortune of others</td>\n\t\t\t<td>Jealousy</td>\n\t\t</tr>\n\t</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Six_root_kleshas_of_the_Abhidharma\">Six root kleshas of the Abhidharma (Buddhism)</span></p>\n\n<p>The <i><a class=\"mw-redirect\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abhidharma-ko%C5%9Ba\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Abhidharma-kośa\">Abhidharma-kośa</a></i> identifies six root kleshas (<i>mūlakleśa</i>):</p>\n\n<ul>\n\t<li>Attachment (<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Raga_(Buddhism)\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Raga (Buddhism)\"><i>raga</i></a>)</li>\n\t<li>Anger (<i><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pratigha\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Pratigha\">pratigha</a></i>)</li>\n\t<li>Ignorance (<i><a class=\"mw-redirect\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Avidya_(Buddhism)\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Avidya (Buddhism)\">avidya</a></i>)</li>\n\t<li>Pride/Conceit (<i><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/M%C4%81na\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Māna\">māna</a></i>)</li>\n\t<li>Doubt (<i><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vicikitsa\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Vicikitsa\">vicikitsa</a></i>)</li>\n\t<li>Wrong view/False view/Opinionatedness (<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/View_(Buddhism)\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"View (Buddhism)\"><i>dṛiṣṭi</i></a>)</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>In the context of the <a class=\"mw-redirect\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yogacara\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Yogacara\">Yogācāra</a> school of Buddhism, Muller (2004: p.&nbsp;207) states that the Six Klesha arise due to the &quot;...reification of an &#39;imagined self&#39; (Sanskrit: <i><i lang=\"sa-Latn\" title=\"International Alphabet of Sanskrit transliteration\">satkāya-dṛṣṭi</i></i>)&quot;.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p><strong>Five Thieves in Sikhism:</strong></p>\n\n<table class=\"vertical-navbox nowraplinks\" height=\"338\" style=\"float: right; clear: right; margin: 0px 0px 1em 1em; background: rgb(249, 249, 249) none repeat scroll 0% 0%; border: 1px solid rgb(170, 170, 170); padding: 0.2em; border-spacing: 0.4em 0px; text-align: center; line-height: 1.4em; font-size: 88%; border-collapse: collapse;\" width=\"664\">\n\t<tbody>\n\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t<th style=\"padding:0.2em 0.4em 0.2em;font-size:145%;line-height:1.2em;background-color: lavender; font-size:110%;\"><a class=\"mw-redirect\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sikh_philosophy\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Sikh philosophy\">Sikh beliefs</a></th>\n\t\t</tr>\n\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t<td style=\"padding:0 0.1em 0.4em;text-align:left; padding-left:0; padding-right:3px;\">\n\t\t\t<ul>\n\t\t\t\t<li>1a. <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Simran\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Simran\">Simran</a> (spiritual contemplation)</li>\n\t\t\t\t<li>1b. <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Selfless_service\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Selfless service\">Sewa</a> (selfless service)</li>\n\t\t\t\t<li><b>2. <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Three_pillars_of_Sikhism\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Three pillars of Sikhism\">Three Pillars</a></b>\n\t\t\t\t<ul>\n\t\t\t\t\t<li>2a. <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Naam_Japo\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Naam Japo\">Naam Japo</a> (contemplating God&#39;s names) Meditating on God&#39;s name to control the five evils and living a satisfying life.</li>\n\t\t\t\t\t<li>2b. <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kirat_Karo\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Kirat Karo\">Kirat Karo</a> (work diligently) Earning/making a living honestly, without exploitation or fraud</li>\n\t\t\t\t\t<li>2c. <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vand_Chhako\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Vand Chhako\">Vand Chhako</a> Sharing with others, helping those with less or those who are in need</li>\n\t\t\t\t</ul>\n\t\t\t\t</li>\n\t\t\t\t<li><b>3. <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Five_Thieves\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Five Thieves\">Five Thieves</a></b>\n\t\t\t\t<ul>\n\t\t\t\t\t<li>3a. <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kaam\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Kaam\">Kaam</a> (lust)</li>\n\t\t\t\t\t<li>3b. <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Krodh\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Krodh\">Krodh</a> (anger)</li>\n\t\t\t\t\t<li>3c. <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lobh\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Lobh\">Lobh</a> (greed)</li>\n\t\t\t\t\t<li>3d. <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Moh\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Moh\">Moh</a> (attachment, e.g. to material things or people)</li>\n\t\t\t\t\t<li>3e. <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hankaar\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Hankaar\">Hankaar</a> (ego, pride)</li>\n\t\t\t\t</ul>\n\t\t\t\t</li>\n\t\t\t\t<li><b>4. <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Five_Virtues\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Five Virtues\">Five Virtues</a></b>\n\t\t\t\t<ul>\n\t\t\t\t\t<li>4a. <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sat_(Sanskrit)\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Sat (Sanskrit)\">Sat</a> (truth)</li>\n\t\t\t\t\t<li>4b. <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Santokh\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Santokh\">Santokh</a> (contentment)</li>\n\t\t\t\t\t<li>4c. <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Daya_(Sikhism)\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Daya (Sikhism)\">Daya</a> (compassion)</li>\n\t\t\t\t\t<li>4d. <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nimrata\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Nimrata\">Nimrata</a> (humility)</li>\n\t\t\t\t\t<li>4e. <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pyaar\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Pyaar\">Pyaar</a> (love)</li>\n\t\t\t\t</ul>\n\t\t\t\t</li>\n\t\t\t</ul>\n\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t</tr>\n\t</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p>Liberation (<i><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Moksha\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Moksha\">mukti</a></i>) means the extinction of all the evils headed by <i>haumai (ego</i>).</p>\n\n<p class=\"firstHeading\" lang=\"en\">&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p class=\"firstHeading\" lang=\"en\"><strong>Seven characteristics of <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nafs\" target=\"_blank\">Nafs</a> in Islam:</strong></p>\n\n<p>In its primitive state the <i>nafs</i> has seven characteristics that must be overcome:</p>\n\n<ol>\n\t<li><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pride\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Pride\">Pride</a> (<i>Takabbur</i>)</li>\n\t<li><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Greed\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Greed\">Greed</a> (<i>Tamaa</i>)</li>\n\t<li><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jealousy\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Jealousy\">Jealousy</a> (<i>Hasad</i>)</li>\n\t<li><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lust\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Lust\">Lust</a> (<i>Shahwah</i>)</li>\n\t<li><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Backbiting\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Backbiting\">Backbiting</a> (<i>Gheebah</i>)</li>\n\t<li><a class=\"mw-redirect\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stinginess\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Stinginess\">Stinginess</a> (<i>Bokhl</i>)</li>\n\t<li><a class=\"extiw\" href=\"https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/malice\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"wikt:malice\">Malice</a> (<i>Keena</i>)</li>\n</ol>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<blockquote>\n<p><em>An interesting question is &quot;What remains once we eliminate all of these vices mentioned across cultures and religions?&quot;</em></p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p class=\"firstHeading\" lang=\"en\">One might answer that nothing, a person will not even act if he has no greed, pride, lust etc to some degree. But, then another question comes up &mdash; Is there an action possible without desire (which is the root element for all of these)? How are you so sure that it is not? How would you be convinced that it is possible? Would you be convinced if you are given some examples, or would you discard those examples? Would you like to experiment with yourself to see whether it is possible, or would you discard the possibility right away?</p>\n\n<p class=\"firstHeading\" lang=\"en\">On a theoretical side, an action is possible only because of energy. Are you convinced that there is no energy possible without desire? You might say that even if such an action is possible, it would be unguided. Yes, but it would be pure. On another perspective, it can also be seen that from infinite possibilities of actions, one takes a guided action only because it is more efficient energy-wise. So, what if you possess enough energy?&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p class=\"firstHeading\" lang=\"en\">From another angle, it can be seen that all of these result from habits which has been built on a very very long time, some are part of evolutionary process or at least have been supported and enhanced by evolution. But, then what about transformations? Can a habit not be transformed? Again, why are you so convinced that it cannot be?</p>\n\n<p class=\"firstHeading\" lang=\"en\">&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p class=\"firstHeading\" id=\"firstHeading\" lang=\"en\"><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Seven_Social_Sins\" target=\"_blank\"><strong>Seven Social Sins</strong></a></p>\n\n<ol>\n\t<li><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wealth\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Wealth\">Wealth</a> without <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Manual_labour\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Manual labour\">work</a>.</li>\n\t<li><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pleasure\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Pleasure\">Pleasure</a> without <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conscience\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Conscience\">conscience</a>.</li>\n\t<li><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Knowledge\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Knowledge\">Knowledge</a> without <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Moral_character\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Moral character\">character</a>.</li>\n\t<li><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Commerce\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Commerce\">Commerce</a> without <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Morality\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Morality\">morality</a>.</li>\n\t<li><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Science\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Science\">Science</a> without <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Humanity_(virtue)\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Humanity (virtue)\">humanity</a>.</li>\n\t<li><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Religion\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Religion\">Religion</a> without <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sacrifice\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Sacrifice\">sacrifice</a>.</li>\n\t<li><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Politics\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Politics\">Politics</a> without <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Principle\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Principle\">principle</a>.</li>\n</ol>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p><strong>Cardinal Values from ancient Greece and Bible:</strong></p>\n\n<ul>\n\t<li><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prudence\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Prudence\">Prudence</a> (<span lang=\"grc\" title=\"Ancient Greek language text\">&phi;&rho;ό&nu;&eta;&sigma;&iota;&sigmaf;</span>, <i>phronēsis</i>; <a class=\"mw-redirect\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Latin_language\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Latin language\">Latin</a>: <i lang=\"la\">prudentia</i>; also <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wisdom\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Wisdom\">Wisdom</a>, <i><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sophia_(wisdom)\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Sophia (wisdom)\">Sophia</a></i>, <i>sapientia</i>), the ability to discern the appropriate course of action to be taken in a given situation at the appropriate time.</li>\n\t<li><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Courage\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Courage\">Courage</a> (<span lang=\"grc\" title=\"Ancient Greek language text\">ἀ&nu;&delta;&rho;&epsilon;ί&alpha;</span>, <i>andreia</i>; <a class=\"mw-redirect\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Latin_language\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Latin language\">Latin</a>: <i lang=\"la\">fortitudo</i>): also termed fortitude, forbearance, strength, endurance, and the ability to confront fear, uncertainty, and intimidation</li>\n\t<li><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Temperance_(virtue)\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Temperance (virtue)\">Temperance</a> (<span lang=\"grc\" title=\"Ancient Greek language text\">&sigma;&omega;&phi;&rho;&omicron;&sigma;ύ&nu;&eta;</span>, <i>sōphrosynē</i>; <a class=\"mw-redirect\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Latin_language\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Latin language\">Latin</a>: <i lang=\"la\">temperantia</i>): also known as restraint, the practice of self-control, abstention, discretion, and moderation tempering the <a class=\"mw-redirect\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Appetition\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Appetition\">appetition</a>. <i>Sōphrosynē</i> can also be translated as sound-mindedness.</li>\n\t<li><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Justice_(virtue)\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Justice (virtue)\">Justice</a> (<span lang=\"grc\" title=\"Ancient Greek language text\">&delta;&iota;&kappa;&alpha;&iota;&omicron;&sigma;ύ&nu;&eta;</span>, <i>dikaiosynē</i>; <a class=\"mw-redirect\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Latin_language\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Latin language\">Latin</a>: <i lang=\"la\">iustitia</i>): also considered as fairness, the most extensive and most important virtue;<sup class=\"reference\" id=\"cite_ref-1\"><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cardinal_virtues#cite_note-1\" target=\"_blank\">[1]</a></sup> the Greek word also having the meaning righteousness</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>Aristotle&#39;s List of Virtues:&nbsp;</p>\n\n<table border=\"0\" cellspacing=\"3\" class=\"wikitable\" width=\"100%\">\n\t<tbody>\n\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t<th bgcolor=\"#E8EAFF\" width=\"24%\"><b>SPHERE OF ACTION OR FEELING</b></th>\n\t\t\t<th bgcolor=\"#E8EAFF\" width=\"24%\"><b>EXCESS</b></th>\n\t\t\t<th bgcolor=\"#E8EAFF\" width=\"24%\"><b>MEAN</b></th>\n\t\t\t<th bgcolor=\"#E8EAFF\" width=\"24%\"><b>DEFICIENCY</b></th>\n\t\t</tr>\n\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t<td align=\"center\">Fear and Confidence</td>\n\t\t\t<td align=\"center\">Rashness</td>\n\t\t\t<td align=\"center\">Courage</td>\n\t\t\t<td align=\"center\">Cowardice</td>\n\t\t</tr>\n\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t<td align=\"center\">Pleasure and Pain</td>\n\t\t\t<td align=\"center\">Licentiousness/Self-indulgence</td>\n\t\t\t<td align=\"center\">Temperance</td>\n\t\t\t<td align=\"center\">Insensibility</td>\n\t\t</tr>\n\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t<td align=\"center\">Getting and Spending(minor)</td>\n\t\t\t<td align=\"center\">Prodigality</td>\n\t\t\t<td align=\"center\">Liberality</td>\n\t\t\t<td align=\"center\">Illiberality/Meanness</td>\n\t\t</tr>\n\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t<td align=\"center\">Getting and Spending(major)</td>\n\t\t\t<td align=\"center\">Vulgarity/Tastelessness</td>\n\t\t\t<td align=\"center\">Magnificence</td>\n\t\t\t<td align=\"center\">Pettiness/Stinginess</td>\n\t\t</tr>\n\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t<td align=\"center\">Honour and Dishonour(major)</td>\n\t\t\t<td align=\"center\">Vanity</td>\n\t\t\t<td align=\"center\">Magnanimity</td>\n\t\t\t<td align=\"center\">Pusillanimity</td>\n\t\t</tr>\n\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t<td align=\"center\">Honour and Dishonour(minor)</td>\n\t\t\t<td align=\"center\">Ambition/empty vanity</td>\n\t\t\t<td align=\"center\">Proper ambition/pride</td>\n\t\t\t<td align=\"center\">Unambitiousness/undue humility</td>\n\t\t</tr>\n\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t<td align=\"center\">Anger</td>\n\t\t\t<td align=\"center\">Irascibility</td>\n\t\t\t<td align=\"center\">Patience/Good temper</td>\n\t\t\t<td align=\"center\">Lack of spirit/unirascibility</td>\n\t\t</tr>\n\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t<td align=\"center\">Self-expression</td>\n\t\t\t<td align=\"center\">Boastfulness</td>\n\t\t\t<td align=\"center\">Truthfulness</td>\n\t\t\t<td align=\"center\">Understatement/mock modesty</td>\n\t\t</tr>\n\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t<td align=\"center\">Conversation</td>\n\t\t\t<td align=\"center\">Buffoonery</td>\n\t\t\t<td align=\"center\">Wittiness</td>\n\t\t\t<td align=\"center\">Boorishness</td>\n\t\t</tr>\n\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t<td align=\"center\">Social Conduct</td>\n\t\t\t<td align=\"center\">Obsequiousness</td>\n\t\t\t<td align=\"center\">Friendliness</td>\n\t\t\t<td align=\"center\">Cantankerousness</td>\n\t\t</tr>\n\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t<td align=\"center\">Shame</td>\n\t\t\t<td align=\"center\">Shyness</td>\n\t\t\t<td align=\"center\">Modesty</td>\n\t\t\t<td align=\"center\">Shamelessness</td>\n\t\t</tr>\n\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t<td align=\"center\">Indignation</td>\n\t\t\t<td align=\"center\">Envy</td>\n\t\t\t<td align=\"center\">Righteous indignation</td>\n\t\t\t<td align=\"center\">Malicious enjoyment/Spitefulness</td>\n\t\t</tr>\n\t</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<h2>Models of Morality</h2>\n\n<p>Philosophers have tried to create models/formulae to know what&#39;s the right thing to do in a given particular situation. Remember, just like with any other models (e.g. physical models) these too are just abstractions of far more complex real situations that exist in society, in the world.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p><strong><a href=\"#\" reactlink=\"/article/178\">Utilitrarian Model:</a></strong></p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;Simple theory &quot;Just do whatever that brings maximum benefit/good for maximum amount of people&quot;. In real life sometimes, it becomes hard to describe what the benefit/good is, and how much variables should we consider e.g. what is good now maybe bad in the long run.</p>\n\n<p>It&#39;s interesting that the our public policies are based on this model only.</p>\n\n<blockquote>\n<p>Formula-1: Calculate the resulting net utility (#positive-#negative) to decide. (Utilitarian/Consequentialist approach)</p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p><strong>Kantian Model:</strong></p>\n\n<p>Kant has done one of the most complex analyses on Morality, so it&#39;s hard to summarize. But essentially, Kant says that in order to decide what is the right thing to do&nbsp;first you have to be free (from natural physical desires which guide your actions normally). An act is moral only when it is done with a right sense of duty <em>(intention matters more than the result)</em>. Effectively, this model demands a person to become free person <em>(sort of selfless)</em> in order to be able to make moral decisions.</p>\n\n<blockquote>\n<p>Formula-2: It is not right if it is not done for the morality&#39;s sake itself, based on free-will/pure-reasoning (Kantian/Categorical approach). Intention matters more than the consequences.</p>\n\n<p>Formula-3: Universalize it, if everybody follows the same way, what happens; if the thing in question loses its essence, then it is immoral/wrong. (Kantian approach). E.g. if everybody keeps breaking the promise, the concept of promise will no longer make sense.</p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p><strong>Principle of Reciprocity and Contracts:</strong></p>\n\n<blockquote>\n<p>Formula-4: Reciprocity; it is moral to reciprocate if there is an implicit contract. It is necessary that all the parties involved in the contract have the same understanding about the contract, nothing is hidden willingly or unwillingly.</p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p><strong>Paternalism:</strong></p>\n\n<p>The idea that State (or any authority figure)&nbsp;can decide on some matters for your own good is called Paternalism.</p>\n\n<p>Example: Does the state have right to coerce me into putting my seat-belt on? I can decide what&#39;s best for me..</p>\n\n<p><span style=\"color:#8e44ad;\"><em>(The deeper question is what gives someone authority to decide for someone else? If it isn&#39;t a power-game, then what is it?)</em></span></p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p><strong>Mills Model for state (government) morality in terms of Freedom:</strong></p>\n\n<p>Mill&#39;s On Liberty book tries to answer &quot;when is legitimate for the state to interfere with our liberty?&quot;</p>\n\n<p style=\"margin-left: 40px;\">1. <strong>Harm Principle:</strong> The only legitimate ground for social coercion is to prevent harm to others. Genuine harm, not offence. [But the problem is what is genuine harm? Is hate speech genuine harm or offence?] Basically it means just physical harm, brutal actions. What about when some has enough drugs for themselves and they just want to be druggie, should the state allow that, they are not trading drugs and harming others? Howevwe in reality, that person is not isolated, he will definitel have impact on others.</p>\n\n<p style=\"margin-left: 40px;\">2. State can interfere in self-regarding situations like that of a drug-addict, suicidal person etc if we can show that their decision is encumbered. Really encumbered<em> (so much that they can&#39;t reason for themselves) </em>like dog-drunk, crazy etc.&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p style=\"margin-left: 40px;\">3. Your freedom might be curtailed if it interferes with freedom of others. But the majorities cannot use this argument to say that some minority who is opposing is attacking their freedom; simply because they don&#39;t need protection of their freedom, they are already in majority. <span style=\"color:#8e44ad;\"><em>[But, they won&#39;t remain majority if they allow it!] </em></span>Even the most whacko ideas need to be heard in a free society.</p>\n\n<p>[<em>&quot;Rich and poor are equally free to sleep under the bridges&quot;</em> - This french joke highlights the thinness of the concept of freedom. The right to free speech doesn&#39;t mean anything if you haven&#39;t been enabled by education to talk well, and to speak and find a place to speak. The most fundamental right, to survive, even that can&#39;t be secured if you don&#39;t have money to eat. - <a href=\"http://rickroderick.org/\" target=\"_blank\">Rick Roderick</a>]</p>\n\n<p><span style=\"color:#8e44ad;\"><em>[Freedom is not really freedom if you aren&#39;t capable of obtaining the pre-requisite necessities to achieve that freedom and the sense of responsibility that comes with it. Like cutting the wings of a bird and saying it&#39;s free to fly. Even if you haven&#39;t cut the wings of a bird, saying that a handicap bird is &quot;free to fly&quot; is ridiculous at best.&nbsp;<strong>You are free to struggle, free to try,&nbsp;everything else is an illusion.</strong>]</em></span></p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>How thick the notion of freedom has to be? Karl Marx&#39;s <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/From_each_according_to_his_ability,_to_each_according_to_his_need\" target=\"_blank\">From Each According To His Ability To Each According To His Need</a></p>\n\n<p><strong>Hegel&#39;s thought on Freedom:</strong></p>\n\n<p>Freedom is something that people have used to overcome obstacles while pursuing their concrete goals. <em>[So, by this model whatever is done to pursue one&#39;s goals is right.]</em></p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<h2>\n<style type=\"text/css\">table, th, td {\n  border: 1px solid violet;\n  border-collapse: collapse;\n}\ntable { width: 100%;}\n\nth, td { padding: 5px; font-size: smaller;}\n</style>\n</h2>\n\n<h2>Moral Dillemmas</h2>\n\n<p><span style=\"color:#8e44ad;\"><em>To follow the moral models, the first requirement is to have necessary human conditions e.g Food, Shelter, ordinary Healthcare. A person who is devoid of these basic necessities has no obligation to follow any moral code, whether it is divine or man-made. A man could be called Transcendent if he is capable of adhering to some moral code despite the&nbsp;destitute condition of being&nbsp;devoid of these basic things.&nbsp;</em></span></p>\n\n<p>What should a person (who&nbsp;thinks at the level of humanity, and is compassionate to everyone) do, when he&nbsp; is to decide whether he should participate in nationalistic fight or not?</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; <em>(This question can be framed in many ways with two different contexts which are at conflict with each other).</em></p>\n\n<p>What about situations where moral evaluations have conflict i.e. we have more than one possible alternatives to do the right thing? Many examples have been presented in movies and novels. One which is not unrealistic is the following: -</p>\n\n<p style=\"margin-left: 40px;\">During the times of some war in which your country is trying to protect itself, all your friends are nominating themselves for the war. Your mother is sick at home, and you know that if you leave her and go to war, she would die. What moral choice would you make?</p>\n\n<p>The core process that life uses is <strong><u>survival and continuation of the self.</u></strong> And living entities do whatever they do to carry out that process only*. So, where does the question of right and wrong come from?</p>\n\n<p><em>(But what happens when one gets past the problem of physical survival. Probably, then comes the problem of &quot;Ideal survival&quot;, why do people even care about being remembered after they die?)</em></p>\n\n<p>The highest images of morality demand to overcome this fundamental process of survival. Is morality about winning over this core, fundamental process employed by life? - If yes, then why, how does it make any sense at all?</p>\n\n<p>Each of our actions has some result. The result can be good, bad, somewhat good, somewhat bad on some level. In a chaotic system, a small action, seemingly&nbsp; insignificant, can cause a major result good or bad. How far should the effect of our actions be considered? Is it the sum-total of the effects of actions till the time, that determines whether we are moral or not? If that is the case, first of all it is beyond one&#39;s capability to calculate the actual result of one&#39;s actions in a chaotic system, in fact it is impossible if we do the maths. Second, you are then going to in the direction of Consequentialism. <strong><em>Does the intention not matter regardless of the results?</em></strong></p>\n\n<p>Is it about finding a good balance of the consequences of our actions?</p>\n\n<p>Is conforming to the society, social rituals, norms is what morality is about?</p>\n\n<p>How much should the emotional consequences weigh in? There are people of all kinds, how much should the actions be accounted for while considering the moral standard?</p>\n\n<p>If morality prevents personal freedom, and personal well-being in turn, should it still be taken seriously? How do we find the balance, when each of our actions have not only effect on ourselves, but on others as well as the collective (society)?</p>\n\n<p>If a person does not &quot;know&quot; that the action is wrong, is it still wrong? It sure might have negative consequences, but is it wrong though if he is not aware?</p>\n\n<p>What if a person has heard about the action that it&nbsp;is considered wrong in some way, but does not believe it so, is it still wrong? - Then, what is right - one that is favoured by the most? Is majority always right? Or, is it the competition b/w schools and the one who wins (asserts more successfully, infests most population) is morally correct?</p>\n\n<p>What about this:</p>\n\n<blockquote>\n<p>Nothing is wrong in itself, nothing is right in itself. You should do whatever you want, whatever makes you happy. (<span jsslot=\"\"><span data-dobid=\"hdw\">carte blanche)</span></span></p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>It <em>can</em> have some greatly negative consequences. No rule means anarchy.</p>\n\n<p>Maybe it makes you happy, but brings negative consequences (suffering) to others. The question is - how much should other people tolerate these negative consequences to allow you to make yourself happy? You say who is the judge? - The social consciousness itself is the judge, it will manifest in way or the other.</p>\n\n<p>Does the intention matter, or does the consequence only matter in deciding the morality of an action?</p>\n\n<p>How much should the situation, context be weighed in while considering some action moral or immoral? And what kind of situations?</p>\n\n<p>What if I choose from possible set of actions, the one that is Lesser Evil? Is that moral? - Who decides that possible set of actions, and how much effort should you put in before finalizing that set?</p>\n\n<p><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Samaritan%27s_dilemma\">Samaritan&#39;s Dillemma</a> - Is charity really moral, because it can potentially make the recipient slothful?</p>\n\n<p>What about the situations when the virtues enact give rise to conflict e.g. between loyality to family members and duty to the larger community? - Socrates discusses this in<em> Euthyphro</em>.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>https://www.csus.edu/indiv/c/chalmersk/econ184sp09/johnrawls.pdf</p>\n\n<p>Theories of Distributive Justice:</p>\n\n<p><a href=\"https://plato.stanford.edu/entries/libertarianism/\" target=\"_blank\">Libertarian</a> - Free-market. Equal Opportunity. An improvement over aristocratic and caste system.</p>\n\n<p><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Meritocracy\" target=\"_blank\">Meritocracy</a> - Fair equality of opportunity.&nbsp;But still the results would not be fair. It would be biased in favour of those who happen to be born in favorible conditions, or even in favourable situations. The same opportunity may have different potential for different people based on pure genetics for example, which is a kind of lottery.&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>You can&#39;t&nbsp;equalize the results, so the best way to go ahead is to distribute the results in favour of those at the bottom.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hopwood_v._Texas</p>\n\n<p>https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PGA_Tour,_Inc._v._Martin</p>\n\n<p>Teleological Moral Reasoning</p>\n\n<p>Coercion is wrong - If you coerce someone into being something that&#39;s not fitting to them, it is plain wrong. - Aristotle&#39;s Teleological View</p>\n\n<p>Moral Reasonings vs Sentiments e.g. Obligations to the solidarity/community.</p>\n\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>\n\n<h2>Suspicions on Morality and its Origin</h2>\n\n<p><span style=\"color:#8e44ad;\">Nietzsche&#39;s &#39;On the Genealogy of Morality&#39;</span></p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp; Greeks ⟶&nbsp; Christians&nbsp;⟶ Nihilism</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp; Life-mastering beliefs (good health, etc..) in Greeks to life-threatening Slave morality (Abstaining from this, that..) in Christians.&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>What about the origin of morality in East?</p>\n\n<p>But against this suspicion is a wonder.&nbsp;<span style=\"color:#8e44ad;\">Nietzsche</span>&nbsp;talks about how morality was incepted as a power game, to turn the tables. But even if that is true, that&#39;s not the interesting point to focus on. The interesting point to focus is sense of morality in strong persons. It&#39;s not hard to imagine and find in history such people who by no means needed to use morality as tool for power, still they strived for morality because they had a sense for it.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","authorId":null,"subject":"philosophy","tags":["prity=3"],"img":null,"summary":"What is the right thing to do and why? We will explore different statements and reasonings for saying that something is right or wrong.","lastUpdated":"2020-08-29T18:54:26.632+0000"}